itSize><BitOffs>208</BitOffs><Default><Bool>false</Bool></Default></SubItem><Method><Name>Pop</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Removes and retrieves an element from the queue (FIFO or LIFO depending on reversed setting)]]></Comment><ReturnType>BOOL</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>8</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>element</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Variable to receive the popped element]]></Comment><Type>AnyType</Type><BitSize>128</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>anytypeclass</Name><Value>ANY</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Properties><Property><Name>hasanytype</Name></Property></Properties></Method><Method><Name>__getisFull</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Returns TRUE if the queue is at maximum capacity

## Detailed Description

Returns TRUE if the queue is full (at maximum capacity), FALSE otherwise.
This property delegates directly to the underlying anyBuffer.isFull property.

Use this property to check if Push operation would succeed before attempting to
add an element.

### Return Value
- **TRUE**: Queue is full (elementCount = capacity)
- **FALSE**: Queue has space for more elements

### Usage Example
```iecst
IF NOT fifo.isFull THEN
    value := 100;
    fifo.Push(value);  // Safe to push
END_IF
```
]]></Comment><ReturnType>BOOL</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>8</ReturnBitSize><Local><Name>isFull</Name><Type>BOOL</Type><BitSize>8</BitSize></Local><Properties><Property><Name>property</Name></Property></Properties></Method><Method><Name>__getisEmpty</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Returns TRUE if the queue contains no elements

## Detailed Description

Returns TRUE if the queue is empty (contains no elements), FALSE otherwise.
This property delegates directly to the underlying anyBuffer.isEmpty property.

Use this property to check if Pop operation would succeed before attempting to
remove an element.

### Return Value
- **TRUE**: Queue is empty (elementCount = 0)
- **FALSE**: Queue contains one or more elements

### Usage Example
```iecst
IF NOT fifo.isEmpty THEN
    fifo.Pop(value);  // Safe to pop
END_IF
```
]]></Comment><ReturnType>BOOL</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>8</ReturnBitSize><Local><Name>isEmpty</Name><Type>BOOL</Type><BitSize>8</BitSize></Local><Properties><Property><Name>property</Name></Property></Properties></Method><Method><Name>Push</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Adds a new element to the queue (direction depends on reversed setting)]]></Comment><ReturnType>BOOL</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>8</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>element</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Element to add to the queue]]></Comment><Type>AnyType</Type><BitSize>128</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>anytypeclass</Name><Value>ANY</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Properties><Property><Name>hasanytype</Name></Property></Properties></Method><Method><Name>__getbuffer</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Gets or sets the underlying AnyBuffer reference

## Detailed Description

Allows getting or setting the underlying AnyBuffer instance that this FIFO queue operates on.
This enables switching between different buffer instances at runtime without recreating
the FifoBuffer object.

### Use Cases
- Reusing the same FIFO queue with different buffers
- Swapping buffer sources during operation
- Dynamic buffer assignment based on runtime conditions

### Important Notes
- Setting a new buffer does not re-validate initialization
- Ensure the new buffer is properly initialized before use
- The overwrite and reversed settings are preserved when switching buffers

### Unittests
 - GetReturnsCurrentBuffer : verify getter returns the current buffer reference
 - SetChangesBuffer : verify setter updates the buffer reference
 - SwitchBufferAndPush : verify push/pop work correctly after switching to a new buffer
 - SetNullBuffer : verify behavior when setting buffer to null/0
]]></Comment><ReturnType Namespace="Tc3_AnyBuffer">I_AnyBuffer</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>64</ReturnBitSize><Local><Name>buffer</Name><Type Namespace="Tc3_AnyBuffer">I_AnyBuffer</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Properties><Property><Name>property</Name></Property></Properties></Method><Method><Name>Clear</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Removes all elements from the queue and resets to empty state]]></Comment><ReturnType>BOOL</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>8</ReturnBitSize></Method><Method><Name>__setbuffer</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Gets or sets the underlying AnyBuffer reference

## Detailed Description

Allows getting or setting the underlying AnyBuffer instance that this FIFO queue operates on.
This enables switching between different buffer instances at runtime without recreating
the FifoBuffer object.

### Use Cases
- Reusing the same FIFO queue with different buffers
- Swapping buffer sources during operation
- Dynamic buffer assignment based on runtime conditions

### Important Notes
- Setting a new buffer does not re-validate initialization
- Ensure the new buffer is properly initialized before use
- The overwrite and reversed settings are preserved when switching buffers

### Unittests
 - GetReturnsCurrentBuffer : verify getter returns the current buffer reference
 - SetChangesBuffer : verify setter updates the buffer reference
 - SwitchBufferAndPush : verify push/pop work correctly after switching to a new buffer
 - SetNullBuffer : verify behavior when setting buffer to null/0
]]></Comment><Parameter><Name>buffer</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Gets or sets the underlying AnyBuffer reference

